            <h2>Technical Details: How Our PDF Watermarker Works</h2>
            <p>Our PDF watermarker uses the PDF-lib library for adding watermarks:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>PDF Loading:</strong> The PDF document is loaded into memory using PDF-lib's load() method.</li>
                <li><strong>Page Selection:</strong> Based on your scope selection, specific pages are identified for watermarking.</li>
                <li><strong>Watermark Rendering:</strong> For text watermarks, text is drawn on each selected page using drawText() with specified font, size, color, opacity, rotation, and position.</li>
                <li><strong>Image Watermarks:</strong> For image watermarks, the image is embedded using embedJpg() or embedPng(), then drawn using drawImage().</li>
                <li><strong>PDF Regeneration:</strong> The watermarked PDF is saved with all watermarks embedded.</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h2>Best Practices for PDF Watermarking</h2>
            
            <h3>Use Appropriate Opacity</h3>
            <p>For watermarks that protect without obscuring content, use 20-30% opacity. For maximum protection where readability is secondary, use 50-70% opacity. Avoid 100% opacity as it makes documents difficult to read.</p>
            
            <h3>Position Strategically</h3>
            <p>Diagonal watermarks across the center are most effective for protection as they're difficult to crop out. Edge watermarks (corners) are less intrusive but easier to remove. Choose based on your priority: protection vs. readability.</p>
            
            <h3>Use Clear, Legible Text</h3>
            <p>Choose simple, bold fonts for text watermarks. Avoid fancy fonts that become unreadable when rotated or semi-transparent. Helvetica and Arial work well at various opacities and rotations.</p>
            
            <h3>Test Before Distribution</h3>
            <p>Always review your watermarked PDF to ensure watermarks appear as expected and don't obscure critical content. Test on a few sample pages before processing entire documents.</p>
            
